         <abstract>
            <p>The size of the cash discount for prompt payment of invoices is an important element in a firm's credit policy. This paper structures the cash discount decision by focusing on the present value of cash flows between a current credit policy and an alternative policy involving a discount. The discount decision is shown to depend on the difference in timing of cash flows between the two policies, the fraction of credit sales to be paid with a discount, the change in sales volume, the variable costs, the firm's cost of funds, and possibly the bad debt loss rate.</p>
         </abstract>
